  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA level 2 requires documented version control, regression test suite, and traceable build procedures. Achieved when all three controls are demonstrably in place for the CFD solver and hemolysis post-processor.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is a commercial code with documented SQA procedures. Version control via Git, regression testing via vendor-supplied benchmark suite, and build traceability via release notes satisfy Gradation 2 requirements for a Class II MRL 2 assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification at level 2 requires at least one analytical or manufactured-solution benchmark demonstrating correct implementation of governing equations. Hemolysis power-law transport equation must be verified independently of the flow solver.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions applied to the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed order of convergence (1.97) matches theoretical second-order expectation, confirming correct implementation. Navier-Stokes solver verified against lid-driven cavity and Couette-flow benchmarks documented in ANSYS verification manual."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires a mesh convergence study with at least two mesh densities and a documented GCI or equivalent uncertainty estimate. Level 3 additionally requires Richardson extrapolation with three mesh levels and a GCI < 5% on the QoI.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (coarse 4.2 M, medium 8.7 M, fine 17.1 M cells). Richardson extrapolation yields GCI of 2.3% on the relative hemolysis index at the worst-case operating point (3.5 LPM, 3500 RPM). Achieved level 3 exceeds the MRL 2 requirement of level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must be documented with sufficient fidelity to reproduce boundary conditions in the simulation. Flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit must be recorded at each operating point.",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for all 5 flow-speed combinations are fully documented in the validation dataset. Blood analog (glycerol-water, hematocrit 35%) temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C. Boundary conditions in CFD match experimental inlet/outlet pressures and rotational speed to within measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Relative hemolysis index (RH) predicted by CFD compared against experimentally measured plasma-free hemoglobin at all 5 operating points. Mean absolute error of 8.4% across operating points. All predictions fall within the expanded measurement uncertainty band (k=2). The comparison demonstrates adequate agreement for the intended use of identifying worst-case operating conditions; a formal validation metric (E_val) was computed per ASME V&V 20 and found within the validation uncertainty bounds. The required level of 2 specifies qualitative agreement with documented uncertainty; the achieved level reflects quantitative agreement within experimental uncertainty, satisfying the threshold for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI relevance at level 2 requires that the modeled output quantity maps directly to the clinical or engineering decision criterion. The relative hemolysis index RH must be demonstrably linked to the regulatory acceptance threshold.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index RH = (NIH_device / NIH_predicate). This quantity maps directly to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1) used in 510(k) submissions for Class II blood-contacting devices. The link between CFD-predicted hemolysis power-law index and plasma-free hemoglobin is established via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation, which has been validated for centrifugal pump geometries in the open literature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be performed on a geometry and flow regime sufficiently similar to the COU to support extrapolation of credibility evidence. Similarity must be documented for Reynolds number range, impeller geometry class, and hemolysis mechanism.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump — the same geometry used in the COU. Operating range covers all 5 COU flow-speed combinations. Reynolds number similarity maintained. No geometric extrapolation required. The validation dataset is therefore directly applicable to the COU without additional bridging arguments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1 requires acknowledgment of iterative convergence monitoring. Residuals must be reported and a convergence criterion documented.",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via scaled residuals (< 1e-5 for continuity and momentum, < 1e-6 for energy and species). Mass imbalance < 0.01% at all operating points. Solver error is considered negligible relative to discretization and model-form uncertainty at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2 for Class II devices when model influence is Medium. Level 1 acknowledgment that simulation was performed by trained personnel is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Use error not formally assessed per MRL 2 scoping decision. Simulations performed by engineers with documented CFD training and peer-reviewed by a second analyst. No use-error incidents identified during the assessment period."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form credibility at level 2 requires documented justification for turbulence model selection and hemolysis correlation, including sensitivity to model-form choices on the primary QoI.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on prior validation studies for rotary blood pumps (Fraser et al., 2011; Hariharan et al., 2011). Sensitivity study comparing SST k-omega vs. realizable k-epsilon shows < 5% difference in predicted RH at worst-case operating point. Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis correlation selected as the most widely validated model for the shear-stress range encountered in centrifugal pumps."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Fluid properties (density 1050 kg/m3, dynamic viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s) sourced from published blood analog characterization data with documented uncertainty. Pump geometry derived from FDA-published CAD files with dimensional verification against physical measurements (< 0.5% deviation). Rotational speed and flow rate boundary conditions set to nominal experimental values. Sensitivity of RH to ±5% variation in viscosity evaluated and found to produce < 3% change in QoI, confirming that input uncertainty does not materially affect the credibility conclusion. The required level of 2 is satisfied by this documented input characterization and sensitivity evaluation; no formal uncertainty propagation beyond sensitivity analysis is required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1 requires documentation that test samples are representative of the device population. Not formally assessed at MRL 2 when experimental data are used solely for validation rather than design acceptance.",
      "rationale": "Test samples not formally assessed. Validation experiments used a single physical specimen of the FDA generic pump. Sample-to-sample variability not characterized. This is acceptable at MRL 2 given that the COU objective is identification of worst-case operating conditions rather than absolute hemolysis quantification across a device population."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1 requires a qualitative statement that simulation input parameters correspond to the validation test conditions. Full equivalency mapping not required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters not formally assessed beyond qualitative confirmation that CFD boundary conditions replicate experimental test conditions. Inlet flow rates, rotational speeds, and fluid properties in the simulation match the experimental protocol documentation. No significant discrepancies identified during model setup review."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-cpb-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 7 assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels for MRL 2. The 6 not-assessed factors are within scope of the MRL 2 scoping decision for a Class II device with Medium model influence. The CFD model is judged sufficiently credible for its intended use of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under CPB conditions. The relative hemolysis index predictions fall within experimental uncertainty at all 5 operating points, supporting the regulatory acceptance criterion RH < 1.",
